definition.value: A cephalosporin compound having 2-(2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)-2-(methoxyimino)acetylamino and [(2-methyl-5,6-dioxo-1,2,5,6-tetrahydro-1,2,4-triazin-3-yl)sulfanyl]methyl side-groups.
A steroid antibiotic that is isolated from the fermentation broth of Fusidium coccineum.
An alpha-amino acid that is glycine in which the alpha-is substituted by a 3-guanidinopropyl group.

A C9 straight-chain saturated fatty acid which occurs naturally as esters of the oil of pelargonium. Has antifungal properties, and is also used as a herbicide as well as in the preparation of plasticisers and lacquers.
An unbranched alkane containing six carbon atoms.
A divalent metal cation in which the metal is manganese.
An ion of copper carrying a double positive charge.
A D-glucopyranose 1-phosphate in which the anomeric centre has alpha-configuration.
The conjugate base formed when the carboxy group of a carboxylic acid is deprotonated.
A benzenedicarboxylic acid cosisting of two carboxy groups at ortho positions.
An sn-glycerol 3-phosphate compound having unspecified O-acyl groups at the 1- and 2-positions.
A monoatomic monocation obtained from sodium.
A monoatomic monocation obtained from potassium.
A hydrate that is the trihydrate form of atorvastatin calcium.
A monovalent inorganic cation resulting from the removal of the unpaired electron from nitric oxide.
An inorganic anion resulting from the addition of an electron to nitric oxide.
An arsenate ion resulting from the removal of three protons from arsenic acid.
A phosphorus oxoanion resulting from the removal of a proton from the hydroxy group of phosphinic acid.
An arsenite ion resulting from the removal of a proton from one of the hydroxy groups of arsenous acid.
An arsenite ion resulting from the removal of a proton from two of the hydroxy groups of arsenous acid.
An organosulfur compound in which a thiol group, -SH, is attached to a carbon atom of any aliphatic or aromatic moiety.
A monovalent inorganic anion obtained by deprotonation of phosphorous acid.
A divalent inorganic anion resulting from the removal of a proton from two of the hydroxy groups of phosphorous acid.
A divalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of both protons from diphosphonic acid.
A trivalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of all three protons from peroxyphosphoric acid.
A carboxamide derived from a monocarboxylic acid.
